---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <BaseHead title="About — 0xMiikey" description="Co-founder, CTO & CPO at UQPAY. Builder at the intersection of fintech, AI, and global payment infrastructure." />
</head>
<body>
  <Header />
  <main style="max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 4rem 1.5rem 2rem;">

    <h1 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: -0.03em; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--fg);">About</h1>
    <p style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 3rem;">MIIKEY · Co-founder, CTO & CPO · Payment Infrastructure</p>

    <div class="prose">

      <p>
        Serial founder. Started companies across e-commerce, gaming, and consumer internet before
        finding the problem I actually wanted to spend a decade on: the infrastructure layer of
        global money movement. Co-founded <a href="https://uqpay.com" target="_blank">UQPAY</a> — a
        global payment infrastructure company focused on making cross-border transactions faster,
        cheaper, and more reliable. As Co-founder, CTO & CPO, I run both sides of the build: on the engineering side, that means architecture, hiring, and keeping a technical team sharp under pressure; on the product side, it means owning the roadmap, shaping how we go to market, and making the calls on what we actually build — and what we don't.
      </p>

      <img
        src="/images/about-hero.jpg"
        alt="AI and technology — building at the intersection of fintech and intelligence"
        style="width:100%; border-radius:8px; border:1px solid var(--border); margin:2.5rem 0;"
      />

      <h2>AI Is Reorganizing the Work</h2>

      <p>
        The thing I keep coming back to: <strong>AI is not just a productivity tool — it's a
        reorganization of how product development works.</strong> The boundary between "product" and
        "engineering" is collapsing. The question of what a 10-person team can build is being
        renegotiated in real time.
      </p>

      <p>
        For people running technical teams, this creates a specific kind of discomfort. The mental
        models we used to evaluate engineers, structure roadmaps, and decide what to build — those
        models are all up for revision. I write about this because I'm living it, not because I have
        clean answers.
      </p>

      <h2>On payments and crypto</h2>

      <p>
        Payments is a sector that looks solved from the outside and is completely unsolved from the
        inside. The moment you cross a border — whether geographic, regulatory, or currency — the
        friction becomes brutal. Being based in Singapore puts you at the center of that friction
        every day: capital flows, regulatory frameworks, currency corridors — it's all live and
        real here. The work I've spent the last several years on is building infrastructure that
        doesn't apologize for that complexity.
      </p>

      <p>
        An earlier chapter spent deep in blockchain infrastructure turned out to be essential
        groundwork — building protocol tooling, shipping in adversarial environments, and learning
        to treat every design decision as a tradeoff with real consequences. That experience
        shaped how I think about system design: build defensively, move deliberately, and never
        assume the underlying rails are stable.
      </p>

      <p>
        I believe programmable settlement rails will matter — not as a speculative thesis, but as
        an engineering one. The technology is capable. The remaining problems are regulatory
        clarity, UX, and institutional trust — all solvable, all in progress.
      </p>

      <h2>Get in touch</h2>

      <p>
        The best way to reach me is <a href="https://twitter.com/0xmiikey" target="_blank">@0xmiikey</a>
        on X. I respond to thoughtful DMs. Also on <a href="https://github.com/miikey" target="_blank">GitHub</a>
        if you want to look at code.
      </p>

    </div>

  </main>
  <Footer />
</body>
</html>
